\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 This subsequent phase is complete when:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls15\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Every configuration can be selected through the existing benchmark experiment mechanism.\
\ls15\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Every condition runs one autonomous OpenCode session per task.\
\ls15\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The same fixed task subset can run under all conditions.\
\ls15\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The model, task inputs, environment, permissions, and budgets are controlled.\
\ls15\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The benchmark evaluator remains hidden from the agent.\
\ls15\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	6	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Task success, model cost, and runtime are recorded consistently.\
\ls15\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	7	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The full-loop condition can be compared with vanilla, feedback-only, and the major ablations.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The resulting experiment should answer two questions:\
How much does progressively engineering the OpenCode feedback loop improve autonomous coding performance?\
Which cybernetic control mechanisms contribute enough additional task success to justify their cost and runtime?\
OpenCode\'92s custom configuration directory can contain agents and commands, which supports this config-driven approach without requiring a separate orchestration program.  \
